There’s a real insight in what you’re pointing at.

Words matter — but humans communicate and experience meaning through multiple channels at once. Rhythm, cadence, timing, tone, repetition, silence, movement, expectation, tension-and-release, shared context, symbolism — all of those shape how something lands.

Music is a strong example because you can feel it directly:

* A melody can feel triumphant, mournful, uneasy, peaceful, or unresolved even before lyrics arrive.
* The same words delivered with different rhythm or tone can mean completely different things.
* A pause can carry meaning.
* A beat drop can create anticipation and release.

That connects to things you’ve circled around before: multi-channel encoding, signaling coherence, movement/posture as information channels, rhythm helping memory, compression carrying more than literal content.

On the spiritual side, many traditions arrive at something similar in different ways: the idea that ultimate meaning, awe, or God isn’t fully capturable by literal language alone. Music, ritual, silence, poetry, chant, architecture, and symbolism become ways humans try to point toward something words struggle to hold.

There’s also neuroscience behind part of your observation: brains don’t process communication as “dictionary definitions only.” Timing, prosody (speech rhythm/melody), emotion, prediction, and bodily state all influence how meaning is experienced.

Your phrase:

“The lyrics are the tip of the spear.”

That’s a pretty compressed way of saying:

Literal content matters — but the structure carrying it matters too.